This place hits the spot. Flavourful fun and spicy. We got several plates including crispy spinach, samosas, dhal, lamb and chicken appetizer, and chicken Tikka masala. I was blown away with the biryani! Highly recommend and the service makes it so much more special of an experience!

This was really great quality all around. I made the mistake of adding more heat to my chicken tikka masala and absolutely needed the mango chutney to ease the burn. It was still delicious so I’d recommend it. Samosas were really good and the Bombay Palak Chat (crispy spinach, chutney, yogurt) was a great shareable appetizer.
Service was very good but I would skip Keema Pav. Other items were tasty and well priced.

The thali was absolutely lipsmacking amazing, both veg and non-veg. The Chicken Kati wrap had great spices and succulent chicken. Ragda pattice was just like Mumbaikar street Ragda Pattice! Thali had an amazing array of meat curries - button chicken, mutton rogan Josh, lamb curry, tandoori chicken - and veg sabzis - paneer saag, channa masala, dal makhani. By far one of the best thalis I have had. The ambience set an amazing homely feeling for an Indian.  Our host Sameer, served us at the just the right time to balance each dish. Amazing person who took care of our little orders too.
I love this place! I come regularly and the owner is so kind. The staff are always nice and helpful. Food is amazing! 10/10 recommend

Best Indian food in DC. Never disappoints. Quality is always consistent and great customer service! Can't go wrong when ordering from here.
My favorite Indian food in DC! Friendly staff, fresh flavors, and a great price. The Barracks Row location is also great!

Been going here since they opened and it has been consistently great food, fast service, and everything I’ve had on the menu is fantastic. Always recommend lamb or goat biryani but if you want to switch it up, keema pav is a delicious app and Gobi Manchurian is a tasty Chinese-Indian dish.

We ordered the Tikka Masala, which was good, and Chicken biryani, that was lacking nuance. Flavors are heavy handed and tastes like a better version of college Indian food. Staff are extremely friendly and service is above average.

Really glad we found Bombay Street Food (thanks twitter)..ordered a lot of food tonight and loved every dish. The vada pav (potato slider), the gobi manchuriab and bombay palak chat we’re really flavorful and unique. The spice level was perfect for us, probably on the medium to hot side. The chicken biryani and garlic naan were both really good too. I can’t wait to visit when they reopen and can’t recommend it enough.
They continue to mess up my order, each and every time. When I call to let them know they just hang up. Customer service is horrible. But the food is good so... there is that lol.

I have been following the taste of that food for year's. Their hospitality and kindness always bring me back here. Staff are very polite and respectful. Food always taste awesome. Environment is always clean and we'll organized. Thumbs up great food.

This was our first time trying this restaurant and it was amazing! Our server Noor had amazing and  extremely welcoming service. His food recommendations were very tasty as well so I’m glad I asked questions. He was willing to answer all of them and never got annoyed. For the appetizers we tried the samosas and Keema Pav which were very flavorful! We also had garlic naan. For the entrees we decided on the butter chicken which came with complimentary rice as well as the Lamb Rohan Dosh. Our meals were very flavorful and the right amount of spice! My friend and I are African so we like our food well seasoned so Bombay was absolutely delicious. The place was clean and the food was served hot! The tables are well spaced out so they are definitely conscious of COVID standards and also do contact tracing. We will definitely be back. The service that our server (Noor) gave was outstanding!

BEST INDIAN FOOD EVER!!! From the moment that you enter this restaurant the waiters give you a nice feeling. Very congenial hosts, it is a lovely place to hang out with family, friends, or colleagues. All the dishes were very delicious, creative, and beautifully presented  Highly recommended!!!

They had good ambience and worst fresher. The waiter was good and hyped about there Bombay thali which in looks real good but in taste it’s just not an authentic thali or not even a thali the curries are sweeter with heavy cream and cold as the rice. Only good thing is it’s included with 2 pieces of tandoori chicken which is good. The area restaurant surrounded by is completely shady with lot of beggars and street vendors. I you try some authentic food better not go here. It’s Americanized completely that’s why you see good reviews. My wife from Nagpur didn’t like any of there food. TLDR; Good price, good portions, AMAZING taste, and delivers!  Food: I love Indian, food and I can confidently say I've been to all of the 20+ indian restaurants in DC. This place has the best taste out of all of them. Their Butter Chicken is spice well and extremely creamy. Their appetizers are all delicious but on the spicier side. The portions are all big, an entree will fill you up and the appetizers are of a portion to be shared. Mango Lassi was also delicious too.  Price: At around ~$14 per entree, this is on par with most places in DC. But the portions are bigger so well worth the value.  Reservations: Yelp says they take reservation, but in my experience they actually don't. Be prepared to wait a bit during the weekends as it's always packed. I get mainly take out for this reason. But well worth the wait.  Experience: Extremely friendly staff that is prompt with their service without compromising friendliness. The restaurant is clean and the table space is about average for a DC restaurant. I honestly wish they had more room to serve more people.

Bombay Street Food has become one of my regular spots when I have the time to go out for lunch, the food never disappoints, the service is excellent, and the portions are filling. The chicken biryani, tadka daal, and gobi manchurian are great!
The butter chicken was okay, but the naan was amazing. The best I've had in a long time.

One of those rare restaurants where everything tastes really good. Would highly recommend the palak chaat, daal makhni and paneer tikka masala. The mango lassi is a little bit on the sweeter side, but still very delicious. Service is excellent and everything is priced quite reasonably for the portion sizes. A solid option for tasty Indian food in Columbia Heights.

My girlfriend and I love coming to this place from time to time and our experience has always been a positive one until today. We put in our pick order over the phone and the person who answered our call was  rude from the start. We didn't really think much of it at first. Then when she went in to pick up the food, he was awfully rude. He didn't respond to her when she said she was there for a pick up and when she repeated herself, he dismissed her by saying that he was busy. She waited patiently, but after paying he just tossed the card at her and didn't even apologize. We are never coming back.

The restaurant was small, had decent decor and was at a convenient location. However, the older guy who seated me and took my order, didn't make me feel welcomed. The food was "OK" but not much flavor. You're better off trying a small, family owned indian restaurant, that's not a restaurant chain like Bombay, that offers more flavorful food and friendlier service.
Loved both the food and the ambience.

Butter chicken and vada pav was excellent in taste however the other stuff that we ordered it was just ok in taste. Palak chat was too sweet and missing some chutneys. Pav bhaji was disgusting. The masalas were nasty in pav bhaji and again it didnt taste even close to pav bhaji..the gobi manchurian was ok and too dry..I would never go back again.

I also love the tandoori shrimp - normally, I wouldn't eat shrimp at a South Asian restaurant, but these guys know how to do it right. Definitely not to be missed! I usually drink the chai or mango lassi depending on my mood and they certainly quench my thirst for a good old Indian beverage.  The service is very quick and the staff is very kind and cordial. Plus it is reasonably priced and super affordable even for students. Overall, highly recommend it. I bet, once you eat here, you will go back to try some more.

I highly recommend this place and will definitely be coming back!
This place is great. Try the Chili Chicken or, if you are very hungry, one of the biryanis.
Good food, reasonable prices and decent service! Must try the chicken biryani if you are a non vegetarian! Dahi puri is a must have for street food lovers.

This place is exactly what I've wanted from an Indian restaurant. It's hits the sweet spot of atmosphere - large tables with large portions in metal containers coming to you to share with whoever you're eating with. Everything down to the glassware used to serve chai, the serving dishes for parata and naan, and the food itself reminded me of the Indian street food scene. Not so fancy that you have to dress up, and not so cheap that the curry is water. We had samosas to start (2 in 1 order), chicken Tikka masala, chana masala, and alo Gobi parata and garlic naan. Absolutely loved this place - will definitely be coming here again with a much emptier stomach.  Pro-tip: This place gets busy, although Google will tell you there's no wait, get there a little early and put your name down on the list. They told me they'd seat me in 30 min and it ended up being 10.

Yes Yes Yes. The food was amazing and our waiter Neil was Awesome! I am big on customer service and they got it right! Keep up the good work!!!!

Taste of home! Instant homesickness with old Bollywood tunes in the background. Please, please try the appetizers! One of the only place in DC to even offer  Misal Pav. Authentic India Cutting chai (tea). Great datespot with your girlfriend/boyfriend who wants the taste of Indian food. Very friendly staff and Prompt service. Good selections of beers and wines.

So i have to caveat this with the fact the aur conditioner was broken and i was sweating buckets when i was seated and they lost a star off the bat from not communicating this to anyone who walked in. All in all, i would come back here. They could use some ceiling fans. After sitting down abd ordering my food. The attention you get is great. They are always refilling the water and the food comes out in a reasonable time even though they are busy. I ordered the yellow lentils and i was pleasantly surprised by the spices. It was kicked up a notch and was very good. I wonder how close to authentic it was. The garlic naan was quite good as well. If you are going to this place you should show up early and with your full party.
Yum! Excellent service, truly hospitable on a busy packed night. Better sized portions than other spots. New favorite for Indian in DC. Thanks!

Best Indian food I have had on the East coast. The Manchurian is spicy, hot, and most importantly fresh. The main courses are mouth watering and the flavors gently dance across your tongue. Exceptional service and make sure to have the chai.
Wow
Okayish food. :/

I was not ready to eat Indian food at all. I always had bad experience with quality and taste. My friends took me to this great place and absolutely loved it. Food is great, prices are reasonable with the quantities. Very amazed to see an authentic Indian restaurant in DC.

I don’t know anything about authentic Indian food but gauging from the staff and clientele, it appeared that this was the real deal. I’ve always heard that Indian food was spicy but never tasted it until this place. I can barely eat the samosa...maybe it was the red wine before that made my palette extra sensitive to their spices. If I were to describe this place in one word, it would be ONSLAUGHT. This place was an onslaught to the senses. Packed to the brim, if that was Bollywood music now I understand why all the crazed wide eyed Chershire cat smiles, interior decor street slick vibes to PC collage blowup wall... thing, and vibrant colors everywhere. It takes a special personal kind of aesthetic vision to concoct what we experienced. It borders between kitschy and chaotic. At one point I felt like Bruce from Bruce Almighty where the music/people get so loud where you can’t hear yourself think. I’ve read SO MUCH that service was great... hm, off night I guess. I felt like we were invisible, at the bar. They poured water into the glasses of people that were before us, for us! It took the mgr 3X to get the bartender to get to us, and when he finally did he moved slower than molasses. It wasn’t until someone else commented on it when I realized that it wasn’t me and that the guy was in a trance. We watched him screw a cap unto a bottle for a full 2 min before he realized it was already closed. He just kept turning and turning the cap, like how this review keeps going and going... all in all, I think we’ll go back and try some other dishes. Why not? We’re gluttons for punishment.

I love Indian food so I was excited to see the new restaurant on Barracks Row. On our first visit we decided to do the sampling platter for two so that we could figure out what to order next time. It was all good but the butter chicken and spinach with cheese were my favorites. Prices were very reasonable  Welcome to the neighborhood.

We went there after reading the reviews. This is by far the worst Indian food I have had with the word Bombay in its name. I'm from Mumbai so I know my Bombay street food.  If you like substandard food this is your go to place. We ordered vadapav which was mediocre, Gobi Manchurian which had more ketchup than cauliflower, for appetizers. We decided to try the Veg Kohlapuri for main course. The sauce for this curry tasted of uncooked garam masala and the vegetables in it had not been cooked very long for them to get flavorful. The naan was dry and hard. When we mentioned this to one of the people ( I think it was the owner or manager of the restaurant) he said he will let us order one item instead of the veg Kohlapuri. By that time we were ready to head out so we ordered Paneer kathi roll to go, for which they charged us. Well, well, how nice of them, right? Wrong!!! They packed sheek kabab kathi roll instead and this vegetarian was furious to say the least. If you are truly looking for authenticity, this place misses the mark massively.
My favorite, fairly-priced for the quality, Indian food in DC! SO flavorful and great portion sizes.

Great food, decent prices, & exceptional service. Skip on the appetizers, you can eat those anywhere. Dig in to the main entrees, they are mouth-watering. You have to taste their rasmalai. Ate here on 2 evenings during my trip to DC. Would definitely go there next time I visit DC.

Over rated and over priced. Ordered spinach and lamb with naan. Food was tasty just expensive for what you get. The atmosphere doesn't apply to this place as you eat and leave to make room for the next person waiting in line.

Good authentic Indian food. Best part is it's not very spicy and spices are used to enhance flavor rather than dominate the taste completely.  Quantity is pretty decent like the complementary rice is almost full to the biryani bowl level which is a lot.  Overall 5*

This place was awesome! My wife lived in India for a few years, so she know good food when we find it, and this place was spot on. Noor, out waiter was spectacular also, and we have found our new favorite spot.

I ordered Misal Pav. One of the unique Indian dishes to find here. I asked them to make it extra spicy (As it really should be) and they did not disappoint..! One of the few places where I order my Indian food since the test is closest you can get what you get in India.
Amazing food, great service. Efforts have been put into everything, even the choice of songs!

This place is such a gem in Columbia Heights. It's easy to miss among a number of small restaurants on Park Rd. but should NOT be overlooked! The quality of the food is excellent, as was the service. I went with a few friends and we shared some appetizers and the sampler plate as a main dish. They were able to accommodate vegetarian requests for my friend and me, everything we ate along with the garlic naan was absolutely delicious. Plus SO affordable - the entire meal, with enough for leftovers, was $25/pp (*after* tax and tip!). I can't wait to go back.
The food was delicious and amazing. You'll get one of the best experience of Indian food in DC.
Best Indian food, look for Mr. Noor
Lives up to the hype. Taste is very close to Mumbai’s street food, but their medium level is equal to spicy. Friendly customer service. Pav-bhaji, ragda patties and kulfi are a must try.
ISMAIL IS THE BEST , just because of him I will come back!

Finally a good place for Bombay Street Food. Loved the Pav Bhaji, Vada Pav and Misal Pav. Keep in mind the food is on the hotter side. Although they served stale Rasmalai by mistake but replaced it immediately!

They have definitely upped their game since the last time I was there. Food was very good. We had chilli chicken, chicken manchurian, vada pav and mango lassi. The staff was caring enough to bring us complementary dates, and other sweets to break our fast since we were there for iftar.
Great service, cheap prices, big portions, and ASTOUNDINGLY good food. Hands down my favorite Indian restaurant in DC, possibly anywhere, and I can’t recommend it highly enough.

I'm so glad Columbia Heights now has a fantastic Indian restaurant! Bombay Street Food is delicious, with a large (yet not overwhelming) menu. There's a great selection of Indian beer and a full bar. The menu includes twists on classics like a chaat made with crispy fried spinach, as well as beautifully done staples like samosa and a wide selection of delicious spiced sauces over rice. I love the "Monsoon season" menu, which includes spicy Indian snack foods like fried paneer, which comes with a delicious chai. The staff is friendly and efficient, and the space is roomy and clean. I highly recommend this place!
Food was on spicy side. Tasted better than some of other places in the area. Breads could have been prepared better.
Feels like India. Authentic taste of most of the dishes. Affordable prices and super filling.
Great service! I would certainly recommend.
Amazing Indian food - so glad it's in my 'hood. The dinner for two sampler is listed as a "must try" - and truer words were never spoken. Delicious and so much food!

Bombay Street Food's story is a rich one. Anthony Bourdain highlighted their little stall in Mumbai and BOOM! They started a brick and mortar spot and now are bringing their cuisine to the USA via Washington, D.C.  This location is in Columbia Heights just around the corner from the Target. It seems like a small space, but once inside, you see its two rooms can sit many. There's booth seating, table seating, and a large bar.  The service is very good and genuinely friendly.  The food is excellent. They have a large menu, but where they win is their appetizers. I recommend the keema pav. It's a steel pot with minced chicken/lamb and ginger and garlic. It's like a stew and comes with grilled rolls of Hawaiian sweet bread. It easily is a full meal and perfectly seasoned!

I've been eyeing this place for some time now and finally got my stomach ready for all these great Indian spices. My friend and I ordered the bombay palak chat appetizer and the dinner for 2 bombay thali special. The palak was delicious. The crispy texture of the fried spinach and creamy yogurt chutney was perfect. We saved some to dip with with currys.  The thali special includes a bunch of samplers from the butter chicken, lamb rogan josh, saagwala and chick vindalo. It was a lot of food for 2 people and well worth it. My friend and I loved the butter chicken, saagwala and rogan josh. All of these meats were tender and seasoned very well. Beware, if you cannot handle the spices the darker the curry expect the spicier the dish. Overall this is a great place for some authentic Indian food. Prices are reasonable and service here is great. There is plenty of neighborhood street parking in the area.

While the food was good in general, it's not authentic. No one fries the pav in vada pav, for crying out loud. And mango lassi needs to be chilled, not room temperature. If you are fine with compromising on the authenticity, not a bad place to go
Try their Chats, especially Dahi Puri and Palak Chat. Also, ambience and staff are really great.

I love this place. The food is totally amazing, just the right amount of spice, the place is cute and nice. The plate that has all different kind of little plates is the best idea ever to share with your family and friends. I don’t even know how to pronounce the name of this plates, but the stuff is very helpful and even the owner can explain you about any plate. Totally recommended. ♥️
Mumbai street food tasted great! Would not recommend the indo-chinese menu. Wish the mango lassi was served with ice or at least a little bit colder.

Ranks as a very rare find in DC, incredibly delicious food for a good price. Has quickly become one of my favorite places to eat out around the Columbia Heights area as it provides real bang for your buck when it comes to the quality of the food and the service.
All the service is good in here, and the treatment of the workers is very good towards the customers, I strongly recommend this place to all of you, and specially to sunita and her service.
!nice app.
Yummy food and excellent service. Chaat was excellent, so was the biryani. Servings were generous. Very reasonable too. Will definitely come back when in DC.

I live around the corner. My uncle lives close too and is a regular. We also bring our family when they visit. Excellent food! Excellent ambiance! I’m so glad we finally have decent Indian food in the Columbia Heights neighborhood!
Loved the food. Great variety and taste. The staff was very friendly and they cater to dietary restrictions as well.
Very delicious,tasty and quality food with good customer service at reasonable price.
Loved it. Real Indian taste. All Bombay food lovers must go and treat yourself with their delicious taste
Excellent food and great little town atmosphere. Loved it!
Food tasted delicious but a bit over priced.
Great taste and big portions
Great !!!!
The pakora was amazing! It was tricky finding a fulfilling vegan option because a lot of dishes are made with butter.

I kind of blame myself because I went in with really high expectations, but it's nowhere even close to proper Bombay street food. The flavor, spices and ingredients were totally off, and the chicken was old and definitely not marinated.

This place is delicious. I thought I already reviewed it here. Nice, delicious flavor. Good harder to find traditional bombay street foods. I can't recommend this place enough. I hope it stays in business for the rest of eternity.
Love the food

Despite tables being full, was able to be quickly seated at the bar. Food was great and served quickly. Waiter was pleasant and talked us through the foods and how to best eat each of them. Waiter was also attentive to refilling my water very quickly as food was a bit on the spicier side for me.

Good selection of dishes representing street food in Mumbai. While I enjoyed eating everything we ordered, I thought that there was still some room for improvement if they are interested in capturing authentic flavors. Having said that, I am sure that I will be back here again because it's difficult to find some of the dishes on their menu in any other restaurant in DC.

Delicious North Indian finger street food, wonderful hidden gem in Columbia Heights! Although the food is more American-fusion, it's flavorful and peppered with authentic spices. I went with my Yelp Elite buddy Skyler and we enjoyed a wonderful feast.  The Vada Pav (5/5) - Veggie sliders with a spicy potato patty sandwiched between fluffy buttery grilled bun that's soft on the outside and crispy on the inside was divine! We were seriously contemplating getting another round. This was my favorite dish on the menu!  Bombay Palak Chaat (4/5) - Crispy spinach with onions and tomatoes topped with raita (yogurt sauce) and a variety of savory and sweet chutney sauces was tasty. Traditionally, the chaat toppings don't sit on a bed of spinach and instead are on top of crunchy crackers "papri chat", or a samosa, or inside crunchy shells "dahi puri" (which is on the luckily on the menu!). Will opt for the Dahi Puri or Bhel Puri next time!  Dinner for 2 Thali (5/5) - Large sample platter with healthy mix of 3 vegetation and 3 meaty curries + tandoori butter chicken was perfect for sharing and the hefty $35 price tag was well worth it! Even comes with fluffy naan, basmati rice, and crunchy pauper. Of the vegetarian dishes, the savory lentil Daal Makni and spinach Saag Paneer with small chunky cottage cheese pieces were flavorful, while the chickpea-based Choola had a nice spicy kick! The indian curries were quite authentic, they weren't oily and I couldn't taste any cream. The little dishes are a generous portion as we delightfully split up the leftovers to take home.  Delicious affordable meal for $25. Looking forward to coming back for some Vada Pav and exploring other items on the menu!
The best Indian restaurant in DC.
Amazing flavor, unique menu, great service.
Excellent food, good atmosphere.  Very good service.
Great food. Service was hit or miss. If there was one thing I could change it would be the absurdly loud music. Otherwise, good place.
Pretty delicious, and the portions were huge! Service was a little slow but they were slammed so I can't really blame them
Really really great food. It's new here and ya'll gotta check it out
Really tasty food and a great 'hole in the wall' vibe. Get the chai and a house wine. The sampler meal is a great deal for two.
Exquisite Indian food

Came here with the most discerning of Indian food critics, who live in NY. They loved it. Definitely the best quality Indian food in DC- especially for the price point. Yes- it's a smaller space. (Hope they expand!) Yes- it stays busy and there is a wait during dinner. No- they don't take reservations. Yes- the sound system is good (can hear people talk even though the music is playing) Yes- the service should be improved.  But the food alone will have you coming back. No skimping. Great flavors. Delicious.  Definitely don't miss the biryani!
Another authentic Indian taste.Food is so yummy. Try Sekh Kabab, any curry dish. They makes it with lots of Love. Music was so romantic. Place is always full of people. Best for the DATE.
Try Dahi Puri and Ragda Paties for sure!

Delicious! We tried dinner for 2 and everything was amazing.   It included tandoori,  lamb, goat,    chick pea,  and black lentil dishes plus butter chicken,  naan, mango chutney,  raitha, and a dessert.  More than we could eat bir we couldn't stop because it was so good.

I have been here couple of times and tried various vegetarian dishes. Among all of them, Palak chaat.... And Dal makhanni are my favorite here! The staff is very courteous and attentive. Most importantly the owner, Asad is always there in the restaurant to make sure the service is perfect. I have been waiting as to when will they start home delivery. Ohh... and for desserts I'd recommend GulabJamun and Ras malai! I wish they introduce Bombay Falooda sometime in the future.  Plan ahead as this place is more or less always busy. Bon appetite people!
Everything was amazing and the bread bowl is a must. The vegetarian sharing platter did not disappoint.

We were a party of 5 and tried a whole bunch of chaat.  Loved the ragda patti, pav bhaaji, keema pav and dahi puri. The chicken tikka kathi roll was so-so, no where comparable to something like kathi roll company. Masala chai was really good too. The folks in the table next to us got thali and it looked really tempting! That would be on our list the next time we visit

This place is great! It's casual, has a nice bar, super attentive staff, and the food is delicious. I really enjoyed the chili chicken, the lamb Rogan josh, and the lamb biryani. You get a lot of food for the money, especially if you go for the sampler platter for $35.
Most authentic Indian food in DC.
Didn't like the attitude of the manager or whoever was the in-charge. First and Last time...

Busy Indian place that doesn't take reservations.  Food is very good and reasonable.  Their Toli is large and can feed 3 people if you've also ordering an appetizer or two, so order accordingly.  I went in with a group of 7 and they were able to find us a spot in just half an hour.  The owner was friendly and briefly came to our table and chatted with us.   The entrees were a good portion and some of our group ended up taking the food home.  The place is also very metro accessible and is just 3 blocks from the Columbia heights metro.
Finally DC has got a great Indian restaurant

Best place to satisfy your cravings. You get all the bombay street food with exact same taste. Place is very beautifully designed and I love the bollywood music playing in the background. People over here are very friendly and welcoming. Best place to go on your cheat day

Located in Columbia Heights of DC, this new restaurant provides a glimpse into the flavors of India by way of their robust menu. However, during busy times of the day, don't expect to find parking easily. Patrons in this neighborhood are relegated to parallel parking - if there's space available.  That's not the restaurant's responsibility though. Walking in, you'll see a bar and booths with decent lighting, talkative staff, and the wonderful smell of Bombay street food.  The hostess masterfully directs the hordes of customers, and proactively responds to questions.  The food then arrives at the table rapidly. The meat was tender, the sauces spiced with heat and fragrance, and the naan well seasoned with garlic. But, a couple sprinkles of salt may have done the naan justice, but otherwise it complimented the food well. Lastly, when the plates say anything about being spicy, BELIEVE it. It's important to note that the heat didn't mask the flavor of the food though.  Overall, I can see why this place is always packed. The ambiance is good for both dates or a casual hangout, the food was delicious, and the service was quick and helpful.
Excellent service. Casual, family-friendly atmosphere. For a little of everything, I highly recommend the Dinner For Two.
This is great Indian food. Lots of food, good prices, and always busy.  I am so happy this restaurant came to Columbia Heights.

Just had Pakodas and Chai. It was good, nicely presented. However, the decor of this place is quite appalling. In fact, downright embarrassing. The Anthony Bourdain collage on the wall looks like it's made at home using a cheap editing software and then disproportionately enlarged. Same for the Monsoon/Bollywood poster. Also, who wants to be reminded of a person who committed suicide while eating? A good Indian restaurant is not just the food but also its decor. Restaurants like Rasa, Choolah etc. have done such an amazing job. I hope that the owner takes note of this.
Three of us ordered the sampler for two and 4 appetizers and three non alcoholic drinks and tab was $84 with some food to take home. I have be three times and service is always great
Good butter chicken and alo gobi. Moderately priced.
Phenomal!!! If you like Indian food this is the place!!!!

Good food and service, the server was very helpful, pretty much ordered everything for us and have to say it is well received ... had a small line at around 7pm but was seated very quickly and definitely will comeback
I can’t wait to have their butter chicken again
Ordered Kati roll, a monsoon item, extra butter chicken, and the Tali meal for two. Everything was wonderful!! Tali was great to try a bit over everything and good portions.

I have been to this place a several times now. The food is amazing down here. Authentic Indian Food, that I can vouch for. For starters I have only tried Paneer pakoda which come with chai and is pretty awesome. The Goat Biryani is just delicious and is served generously (so even if your stomach get full you can always take it back home for another meal). I love the dal makhani, just order it with some garlic nan and you are sorted. The kababs here sizzle and come to you with that trail of smoke which makes everyone look at you. It tastes better than most of the kababs I have had in India. Finally for dessert I’d suggest gajar ka halwa. Its not super sweet but neither bland. Cooked well. I personally am not a big fan of really sweet stuff, so this was just perfect for me. I m sure I ll be going there soon enough and keep updating here.
A very good place to grab lunch. Good service and good prices for the area, with some good Indian beer. Food is spicy enough for those who want it. Hope to return here

Great food and well priced. We ordered the samosas and dinner sampler for 2 with a mango lassi to drink. Service could slow down a bit and acknowledge the guest more (such as describe the sampler when it's brought to the table - 11 items/sides/sauces + naan and rice). Nice to have in Columbia Heights - will go back.
Amazing good. Order the dinner for 2 to share!
Amazing Tasty Authentic Indian food Great location Nice hospitality Thanks!!!!

Had a great experience here! Highly recommend the vada pav. It's legit and incredibly flavorful. Server staff was wonderful and the prices are reasonable, especially compared to other indian food in the DMV.
amazing food as well as good service .....thank you bombay street food....
Ordered samosas and a thali. It all looked and tasted delicious !
amazing food, incredible service!
Good value and a great addition to the CoHi neighborhood. Their palak chaat gives Rasika's a run for its money.
Really good indian food. The "Dinner for 2 Bombay Thali" was great value given the huge selection that they brought out.
We tried, but they don't do takeaway/carry out when they're "busy".

AMAZING place, love it! Cozy, cute, good prices, delicious authentic indian food. Spicy, delicious, and flavorful food, quick and polite service, even nice music. Been there a shameful 3x in the last two weeks....and still haven't tried the thali so need to go again soon...loveeeee this place.
Great Indian food. Recommend it.

Ordered the butter chicken and garlic Naan. Flavorful and spiced wonderfully-- fast and friendly service, even at the end of lunch service while dining alone. Reasonably priced with a relaxing atmosphere.

Hands down the best Indian I’ve had in the city. It’s spicy and full of delicious flavor. The prices on drinks and food are also very reasonable. This will definitely be my go to spot when I want Indian.

Tasty food with friendly and really quick service. Our food was ready in no time, and everything was hot and fresh. The restaurant is roomier than it looks from the outside. Quite reasonable prices for that locale.

Best place to satisfy your cravings. You get all the bombay street food with exact same taste. Place is very beautifully designed and I love the bollywood music playing in the background. People over here are very friendly and welcoming. Best place to go on your cheat day  :P

Let’s start with what worked- Vada pav was great. Kathi roll was ok and dry.. missed the saucy texture.  What didn’t work- gobi Manchurian was a red sweet tomato sauce dish, usually it’s a brown colored spicy garlic flavor.  Chat was a usual market sauce dish and lacked the authentic flavor which we expected from the restaurant.  Kheema Pav was to go.. we never got the kheema only the bread was there when we got home!!  Silverware and the dishes were very average, so was furniture.. there are many better places around without the buzz in DMV.  Maybe we came with high expectations..when you add Bombay to any name especially if the restaurant is cooking the Bombay street food you always expect the best or quality. I am sure they will work on the menu.
Great, tasty food (dishes advertised as spicy actually had a kick) and really nice staff. Excited to have a good Indian restaurant in Columbia Heights and will definitely be back.

Pretty decent food though the bhel Puri wasnt strong enough and the gobi Manchurian was dissappointing. Beer is cheap and plentiful, and the chili chicken and chicken Manchurian is solid, as is the pav baji. Good service, friendly people.
It was good time in this place good food good service I have fun they are very friendly
Very good food, wonderful hospitality. Parking is available across the street from restaurant just blow Target and Old Navy parking structure, Its paid parking they charge $3 per hour.
